---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Boruto Filler List",
  description: "Skipping filler episodes saves you hours of viewing time. Find out which episodes you actually need to watch to follow the main story.",
  category: "list",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the difference between Anime Canon and Filler in Boruto?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Anime Canon consists of episodes that are not in the manga but are considered official backstory and character development approved by the creator. Filler is entirely unrelated side-content."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I skip all the Anime Canon episodes?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "You can, but it's not recommended. Many Anime Canon arcs introduce characters and concepts that later appear or are referenced in the Manga Canon."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What percentage of Boruto is filler?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "If you count both Anime Canon and pure Filler, nearly 70-80% of the anime consists of original content not found in the monthly manga chapters."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why does Boruto have so much filler?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The Boruto manga is published monthly, while the anime airs weekly. The anime must create original content to avoid catching up to and passing the manga's story."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Which Boruto arcs are the most important to watch?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The core narrative focuses on the Versus Momoshiki Arc, the Mujina Bandits Arc, the Ao Arc, and the Kawaki/Kara Arcs. These are essential viewing."
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": meta.title,
    "description": meta.description
  }
];
---
<SiteLayout site="siliconbased" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://siliconbased.dev/boruto-filler-list" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero"><h1>{meta.title}</h1><p class="subtitle">Your ultimate guide to skipping the filler</p></div>

    <h2>Navigating the World of Boruto: Naruto Next Generations</h2>
    <p>For fans transitioning from the globally acclaimed <em>Naruto Shippuden</em> to its sequel series, <em>Boruto: Naruto Next Generations</em>, one of the most immediate and hotly debated topics is the sheer volume of episodes. More specifically, the discussion revolves around how many of these episodes are crucial to the main overarching plot versus how many are considered "filler." In the context of anime, filler refers to episodes that are created by the animation studio to pad out the runtime, usually because the source material (the manga) hasn't produced enough chapters to adapt yet. This prevents the anime from catching up to the manga and forcing a hiatus. A Boruto filler list is therefore an essential navigational tool for any viewer looking to experience the core story without the fluff.</p>

    <p>Unlike its predecessor, <em>Boruto</em> handles the concept of filler a bit differently, leading to what many fans call "Anime Canon." While traditional filler is often completely disconnected from the main storyline and characters, Anime Canon episodes in <em>Boruto</em> are technically approved by the original creators and serve to flesh out the world, build character relationships, and provide context that the fast-paced manga skips over. However, for a viewer strictly interested in the main conflict involving the Otsutsuki clan, Kara, and Boruto's karma seal, a comprehensive filler list is invaluable for saving time.</p>

    <h2>Understanding Filler, Manga Canon, and Anime Canon</h2>
    <p>To use a Boruto filler list effectively, it's crucial to understand the three distinct categories of episodes. The first is <strong>Manga Canon</strong>. These episodes are direct, faithful adaptations of the monthly <em>Boruto</em> manga chapters. They contain the highest stakes, the most significant plot developments, and are absolutely essential viewing. The second category is <strong>Anime Canon</strong>. As mentioned, these episodes are unique to the anime but expand upon the manga's events. For example, the Academy Entrance Arc or the Hidden Mist Field Trip Arc are considered Anime Canon. They aren't in the manga, but they establish characters like Sumire and Kagura, who appear later or influence main plot points.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Core Structural Concept: The Pacing Ratio</strong><br/>
      The fundamental reason for the extensive filler in <em>Boruto</em> is the pacing ratio between the manga and the anime. The <em>Boruto</em> manga is published monthly, typically releasing around 40 pages of content. In contrast, the anime is broadcast weekly. It is mathematically impossible for a weekly anime to sustain itself purely on a monthly manga without rapidly overtaking it. Therefore, the animation studio must generate original content (Anime Canon and Filler) to maintain the weekly broadcast schedule while allowing the manga time to progress.
    </div>

    <p>The third and final category is true <strong>Filler</strong>. These are standalone episodes or short arcs that have virtually no impact on the broader narrative. They often involve comedic situations, minor missions, or side characters dealing with low-stakes problems. While some fans enjoy these lighthearted breaks, viewers focused on the primary storyline generally skip them. A good Boruto filler list will clearly delineate these three categories, allowing the viewer to make an informed decision about what to watch based on their available time and investment level.</p>

    <h2>Real-World Examples of Skipping vs. Watching</h2>
    <p>Let's consider a practical example of how utilizing a filler list alters the viewing experience. A fan who decides to watch every single episode of <em>Boruto</em> will spend hundreds of hours consuming content that includes episodes about Cho-Cho acting in a soap opera or Wasabi dealing with a minor dispute. While charming in their own right, these episodes severely disrupt the pacing of the main, tension-filled arcs involving deadly threats like Momoshiki or Isshiki Otsutsuki.</p>

    <p>Conversely, a viewer who strictly follows the Manga Canon route will experience a streamlined, fast-paced, and highly focused narrative. However, they might also miss out on crucial character development for Boruto's classmates (like Shikadai, Inojin, and Sarada), making their eventual involvement in major battles feel unearned or confusing. This is why many community-curated filler lists recommend a hybrid approach: watch the Manga Canon, selectively watch the highly-rated Anime Canon arcs that expand the lore, and entirely skip the purely comedic or irrelevant true filler.</p>

    <h2>The Evolution of the Anime Landscape</h2>
    <p>The existence and necessity of a Boruto filler list also speak to broader trends in the anime industry. In the past, long-running shonen series like <em>Naruto</em>, <em>Bleach</em>, and <em>One Piece</em> were notorious for long stretches of filler. These shows operated on a continuous weekly broadcast model, prioritizing constant airtime over pacing.</p>

    <p>Modern anime, such as <em>Demon Slayer</em>, <em>Jujutsu Kaisen</em>, or <em>Attack on Titan</em>, have largely shifted to a seasonal model. They produce a set number of episodes (usually 12 or 24), adapt the available manga faithfully, and then take a break until more source material is ready. This eliminates the need for filler entirely and results in a consistently high-quality, fast-paced narrative. <em>Boruto</em>, as a continuation of a legacy franchise, inherited the older, continuous broadcast model, making its filler list a necessity rather than an option for modern viewers accustomed to seasonal pacing.</p>

    <h2>How to Read and Apply a Filler List</h2>
    <p>When you consult a Boruto filler list, you will typically encounter a color-coded chart or a simple text breakdown. The list will group episodes by their arc and explicitly label them. Here is a general strategy for applying the list:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Identify the Core Arcs:</strong> Locate the major Manga Canon arcs first (e.g., the Versus Momoshiki Arc, the Mujina Bandits Arc, the Vessel Arc, and the Kawaki Arc). These are your non-negotiable watch points.</li>
        <li><strong>Evaluate Anime Canon:</strong> Look at the Anime Canon arcs surrounding the core arcs. Read brief, spoiler-free summaries to determine if they interest you. The Kara Actuation Arc, for instance, is highly recommended as it provides vital backstory for the villains before they appear in the manga adaptation.</li>
        <li><strong>Ruthlessly Skip True Filler:</strong> If an episode or arc is labeled purely as filler, unless it features a side character you absolutely love, skip it. You will not miss any essential plot points.</li>
        <li><strong>Check for Mixed Episodes:</strong> Be careful with episodes labeled "Mixed Canon/Filler." These episodes often start with filler content but end with a crucial scene that sets up the next major arc. Fast-forwarding or reading a summary of these episodes is often the best approach.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Advanced Viewing Strategies</h2>
    <p>For the truly dedicated fan who wants the most optimal viewing experience, creating a custom watch order is the best approach. This involves taking a standard Boruto filler list and tailoring it. You might decide to watch all the Anime Canon arcs that focus on the Uchiha family (Sasuke and Sarada) but skip the ones focusing on Team 15 or Team 5. This level of customization allows you to stay engaged with the characters you care about most without feeling bogged down by the sheer volume of episodes.</p>

    <p>Another advanced strategy involves utilizing fan-edits. In the same way that "Naruto Kai" condensed <em>Naruto Shippuden</em> by removing all filler and repeated flashbacks, fan communities occasionally create condensed versions of <em>Boruto</em> arcs. While these are unofficial, they represent the ultimate application of a filler list, turning a 20-episode Anime Canon arc into a streamlined, feature-length movie experience.</p>

    <h2>Why It Matters</h2>
    <p>Your time is valuable. With the sheer amount of incredible media available today, committing hundreds of hours to a single anime series is a significant investment. A Boruto filler list empowers you, the viewer, to reclaim your time and curate your own entertainment experience. It prevents burnout—a common phenomenon where viewers drop a potentially great show because they get stuck in a tedious 20-episode filler arc about an irrelevant ninja ostrich or a rogue chef.</p>
    <p>Furthermore, using a filler list respects the original artistic intent of the manga creators. While the animation studio's original content has its place, the core narrative crafted by Ukyo Kodachi and Masashi Kishimoto is the beating heart of the franchise. By focusing on the Manga Canon, you experience the story exactly as it was intended to be told: a high-stakes, emotional continuation of the ninja world's legacy, focusing on the new generation's struggles against unprecedented threats.</p>

    <h3>Cultural Impact and Discussion</h3>
    <p>The discussion around the Boruto filler list also fosters a unique sense of community. Anime forums, subreddits, and social media platforms are filled with passionate debates about which Anime Canon arcs are worth watching and which ones should be skipped. These discussions help new viewers navigate the daunting episode count and provide a shared space for fans to analyze the pacing, animation quality, and character development of the series.</p>

    <p>In conclusion, a Boruto filler list is not just a simple guide; it is a critical tool for navigating one of the most popular, yet structurally complex, anime series of the modern era. It allows fans to experience the thrilling highs of the overarching narrative without getting bogged down by the unnecessary lows of studio-mandated padding.</p>

